  1.🥲 🧠 Deadlock Avoidance (Resource Allocation Graph Algorithm)

       Deadlock avoidance ensures the system never enters an unsafe state.

         👉 It uses a Resource Allocation Graph (RAG) with:

          Process nodes (P)
          Resource nodes (R)
          Claim edges (possible future requests)

         ⚙️ Idea:
             Before allocating a resource, OS checks:
             👉 “Will this create a cycle in the graph?”
             If cycle forms → do NOT allocate
             If no cycle → safe to allocate    

     2.✌️ Deadlock Avoidance part 2 | Banker's algorithm | safety algorithm in deadlock avoidance       
        🧠 Banker’s Algorithm (Deadlock Avoidance)

           It is used to avoid deadlock by checking whether the system is in a safe state before allocating resources.
           
           👉 A request is granted only if the system remains safe 

          🧠 Safety Algorithm

               Used to check whether the system is in a safe state
               
               ⚙️ Steps:
               Find a process whose Need ≤ Available
               Allocate resources → assume it finishes
               Release its resources back
               Repeat for all processes
               
               👉 If all processes finish → Safe state
               👉 Else → Unsafe state 

               ⚠️ Terms to Remember:
                   Available → free resources
                   Max → maximum need
                   Allocation → currently given
                   Need = Max − Allocation

                   